Suddenly from below, clac!
clac!
two dry hands are clapped together; it is Madame Prune's warning to the Great Spirit.
And immediately after her prayer breaks forth, soars upward in a shrill nasal falsetto, like a morning alarum when the hour for waking has come, the mechanical noise of a spring let go and running down.
"...
The richest woman in the world!
Cleansed from all my sins, O Ama-Terace-Omi-Kami!
in the river of Kamo."
And this extraordinary bleating, hardly human, scatters and changes my ideas, which were very nearly clear at the moment I awoke
